snippet: Several candidates criticized Senator Elizabeth Warren’s health care proposal and backed proposals to impose big taxes on the wealthy.
lead_paragraph: Good Wednesday. This year’s DealBook Summit will feature speakers like Bill Gates, Hillary Clinton, Ginni Rometty of IBM and Makan Delrahim, the head of the Justice Department’s antitrust division. Apply to attend here. (Sign up here to get this in your inbox each morning.)
abstract: Several candidates criticized Senator Elizabeth Warren’s health care proposal and backed proposals to impose big taxes on the wealthy.

snippet: Tuesday’s debate — the tensest yet — put the Democrats’ newly minted front-runner to the test.
lead_paragraph: If you had any question before Tuesday night’s debate about which Democratic presidential candidate is effectively the front-runner, the first half-hour answered it.

headline_main: It Was the Best of Warren. It Was the Worst of Warren.

snippet: Elizabeth Warren fielded all the attacks that being a front-runner brings, and Pete Buttigieg and Amy Klobuchar made their cases as moderate alternatives.
lead_paragraph: Twitter can’t tell us whether, or how, Tuesday’s CNN/New York Times debate might change voters’ minds. But it can give us the perspectives of some of the people with expertise on primary races: veteran campaign strategists and consultants from both parties.

headline_main: Who Won the Debate? Experts Weigh In

snippet: The Midwestern centrists are the only two plausible not-Biden candidates.
lead_paragraph: The ridiculous number of candidates on the Democratic stage last night created a fundamentally misleading aural and visual impression. Watching without access to polling data, you might have imagined that this was some sort of wild careening mess of a primary race, when really it’s remarkably consolidated.
abstract: The Midwestern centrists are the only two plausible not-Biden candidates.

snippet: North Korea’s state news agency said the dictator’s eyes were “full of noble glitters” during his Putin-esque photo shoot.
lead_paragraph: It was a striking scene, of the leader of a nuclear-armed nation astride his majestic horse.

snippet: Elizabeth Warren was called out by rivals for a change, Joe Biden failed to stand out and Bernie Sanders calmed concerns about his health. Pete Buttigieg had his biggest night yet.
lead_paragraph: WESTERVILLE, Ohio — The CNN/New York Times debate on Tuesday night revealed new dynamics in the Democratic presidential race: Senator Elizabeth Warren took sustained fire from multiple rivals, former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. struggled to make an impact and Mayor Pete Buttigieg and other candidates were newly aggressive in making their points.
abstract: Elizabeth Warren was called out by rivals for a change, Joe Biden failed to stand out and Bernie Sanders calmed concerns about his health. Pete Buttigieg had his biggest night yet.

headline_main: 6 Takeaways From the October Democratic Debate
byline_original: By Shane Goldmacher and Reid J. Epstein

snippet: After decades of trying to prove their toughness on national security, the candidates described an allies-first, tough-on-Russia foreign policy. But many of them, too, want to withdraw from the Middle East.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — For nearly two decades, Republicans have dominated national security debates, portraying themselves as tough on terrorists after the Sept. 11, 2001, attacks and tough on a recalcitrant, disruptive Russia. On Tuesday night, Democrats sensed an opportunity to retake that ground, attacking President Trump’s impulsive action in Syria as a gift to the Islamic State and to President Vladimir V. Putin of Russia.
abstract: After decades of trying to prove their toughness on national security, the candidates described an allies-first, tough-on-Russia foreign policy. But many of them, too, want to withdraw from the Middle East.

snippet: Her reward for a steady rise in the polls? Criticism from her debate rivals.
lead_paragraph: WESTERVILLE, Ohio — Senator Elizabeth Warren looked down, performatively taken aback. She raised her hand to speak — surely it was her turn again. She shrugged a little.
